#eNCA Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Bus company Intercape says it won't go down without a fight. That's following a spate of attacks against its buses and drivers. The company says there have been at least 150 violent incidents over the last year leading to staff and passengers being injured. Last week, the violence reached its peak when a driver was gunned down outside the Cape Town bus depot. READ: Crime in SA | Intercape calls for more protection Bangikhaya Machana was shot moments after leaving the Intercape bus depot on 25 April. He died a few days later in hospital. Intercape says it's stepping up security measures, even considering allowing drivers who are licenced gun owners to drive with firearms. * eNCA's Monique Mortlock reports.